body:
Since the `"sass"` key is only used by Sass, and Sass already handles resolving file extensions automatically, you should be able to manually specify that only one of the possible resolutions is valid:

```json
{
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "sass": "./packages/index.scss",
      "default": "./packages/index.js"
    },
    "./*": "./*",
    "./packages/*": {
      "sass": null,
      "default": "./packages/*.js"
    },
    "./packages/*.js": "./packages/*.js",
    "./packages/*.scss": {
      "sass": null,
      "default": "./packages/*.scss"
    },
    "./package.json": "./package.json"
  }
}
```

This way, Sass files will only ever use `"./*": "./*"` (which I believe makes the last few lines redundant anyway) and not see multiple possible candidates.

That said, I don't think it would hurt anything to avoid raising an error if it finds only identical candidates.
